  {# ── Overview ── #}
  <h2 id="overview" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600 vf-search-client-side--no-index">Overview</h2>

  <p>Modern websites often use third-party dependencies such as analytics tools, UI libraries, embedded widgets, video players, social sharing tools, and API integrations. These provide functionality quickly without having to build everything in-house.</p>

  <p>A third-party dependency is any external resource loaded from another domain or managed by an external provider (e.g. analytics scripts, ads, chat widgets, or embedded media).</p>

  <p>While useful, these dependencies can negatively impact performance, reliability, and security. In low-resource environments (LRO), the impact is amplified because each dependency:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Adds extra network requests</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Increases total page weight</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Can block rendering while scripts load and execute</li>
  </ul>

  {# ── Why does this matter for LRO? ── #}
  <h2 id="why-lro" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Why does this matter for LRO?</h2>

  <p>On slower networks and older devices, third-party scripts are often a major source of performance problems. They can:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Compete with essential content for bandwidth</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Add more network requests</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Block the browser's main thread</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Delay rendering and user interactions</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Cause layout shifts or delay critical content</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Because these scripts are controlled by external providers, developers have limited control over how efficiently they load. A single poorly optimised widget or analytics script can significantly slow the experience.</p>

  <p><strong>The key principle is:</strong> Essential content must load first. Third-party functionality must never block the core experience.</p>

  <p>A good LRO strategy ensures external features are carefully controlled so the page remains fast, usable, and resilient on slow networks and low-end devices.</p>

  {# ── Types of Third-Party Dependencies ── #}
  <h2 id="types" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Types of Third-Party Dependencies</h2>

  <p>Third-party dependencies generally fall into four main categories.</p>

  <h3>Libraries and Frameworks</h3>

  <p>Reusable code used for UI components, charts, data processing, or utilities.</p>

  <p><strong>Examples:</strong> chart libraries, UI frameworks, date libraries</p>

  <p>These can significantly increase bundle size if not carefully managed.</p>

  <h3>Plugins and Extensions</h3>

  <p>Prebuilt components that add specific functionality to a page.</p>

  <p><strong>Examples:</strong> cookie banners, pop-ups, search widgets, comment systems</p>

  <p>These often load additional scripts and styles from external servers.</p>

  <h3>APIs and Microservices</h3>

  <p>External services that provide data or functionality through API calls.</p>

  <p><strong>Examples:</strong> mapping services, translation APIs, payment gateways, authentication systems</p>

  <p>API dependencies introduce latency and potential reliability issues if the external service becomes slow or unavailable.</p>

  <h3>Embedded Widgets</h3>

  <p>Visual elements loaded from external services.</p>

  <p><strong>Examples:</strong> video players, social media embeds, analytics dashboards, ads</p>

  <p>Embedded widgets often load multiple scripts, stylesheets, and network requests.</p>


  <h2 id="third-party-dependencies" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">How Third-Party dependencies load</h2>
