  {# ── Common Problems with Third-Party Dependencies ── #}
  <h2 id="common-problems" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Common Problems with Third-Party Dependencies</h2>

  <h3>Excessive Network Requests</h3>

  <p>Each dependency may require multiple requests, including scripts, styles, fonts, and tracking endpoints, increasing page load time.</p>

  <h3>Render-Blocking Scripts</h3>

  <p>Some scripts block rendering until fully loaded, causing blank screens.</p>

  <h3>Main Thread Blocking</h3>

  <p>Heavy scripts consume CPU and delay interactions, leading to slow input responsiveness on low-power devices.</p>

  <h3>Poor Caching</h3>

  <p>Inefficient caching in many third-party scripts can force repeated downloads, increasing data usage.</p>

  <h3>Uncontrolled Updates</h3>

  <p>Automatic updates may introduce breaking changes or performance regressions. Use version pinning to maintain stability.</p>

  {# ── Risk Assessment for Third-Party Dependencies ── #}
  <h2 id="risk-assessment" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Risk Assessment for Third-Party Dependencies</h2>

  <p>Before integrating a dependency, developers should assess its impact.</p>

  <h3>Key Questions</h3>

  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Is it essential to the user experience?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Can this be built natively instead?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">What is the performance cost?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Does it introduce security risks?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Is it actively maintained?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">What happens if it fails or is unavailable?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Careful evaluation helps avoid unnecessary dependencies and protects performance, reliability, and user experience, especially in low-resource environments.</p>

  {# ── Dependency Audit Checklist ── #}
  <h2 id="audit-checklist" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Dependency Audit Checklist</h2>

  <p>Teams should regularly audit third-party dependencies.</p>

  <p>For each dependency, check:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Is it still needed?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">What is its size and network impact?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Does it block rendering?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Is it actively maintained?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Does it introduce security vulnerabilities?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Can it be replaced with a lighter option?</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Can it be self-hosted?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Use automated tools to identify unused or costly dependencies.</p>

  <p><strong>Tools:</strong> Lighthouse, WebPageTest, Chrome DevTools (Network panel), Bundle analysers</p>

  {# ── Implementation Guidance ── #}
  <h2 id="implementation" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400">Implementation Guidance</h2>

  <h3>Minimise Dependencies</h3>

  <p>The simplest optimisation is to reduce the number of external libraries used.</p>

  <p>Fewer dependencies reduce:</p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Network requests</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Security risks</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Maintenance complexity</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Performance overhead</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Minimising dependencies also reduces the application's attack surface.</p>

  <h3>Load Scripts Asynchronously</h3>

  <p>The browser cannot continue rendering the page while a synchronous script is loading and running. Third-party scripts should rarely block rendering.</p>

	<figure class="vf-figure vf-figure--align vf-figure--align-centered">
		<img src="{{ '/images/content_images/LRO diagram 3.2.4b.avif' | url }}" alt="" loading="lazy">
		<figcaption class="vf-figure__caption"></figcaption>
	</figure>
  <p>Third-party scripts should rarely block rendering.</p>

  <p><strong>Example #1:</strong></p>
  <pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>&lt;script async src="analytics.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>

	<figure class="vf-figure vf-figure--align vf-figure--align-centered">
		<img src="{{ '/images/content_images/LRO diagram 3.2.4c.avif' | url }}" alt="" loading="lazy">
		<figcaption class="vf-figure__caption"></figcaption>
	</figure>
  <p><strong>Example #2:</strong></p>
  <pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>&lt;script defer src="analytics.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>

	<figure class="vf-figure vf-figure--align vf-figure--align-centered">
		<img src="{{ '/images/content_images/LRO diagram 3.2.4d.avif' | url }}" alt="" loading="lazy">
		<figcaption class="vf-figure__caption"></figcaption>
	</figure>

  <p>Async downloads scripts while the page continues rendering. <code>defer</code> executes the script after HTML parsing completes.</p>

  <h3>Lazy Load Third-Party Resources</h3>

  <p>Non-critical resources should load only when required.</p>

  <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Loading video embeds when users scroll near them</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Loading analytics after page interaction</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Loading ads only when visible</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Lazy loading defers loading of non-critical content until it is actually needed (e.g., when it enters the viewport). This reduces initial download size, speeds up page load, and saves CPU and network resources, which is especially important for low-resource devices.</p>

  <h3>Example: Lazy Loading with IntersectionObserver</h3>

  <pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>// Select the element to lazy load (e.g., a widget or image)
const widget = document.querySelector('#lazy-widget');

// Create an IntersectionObserver to monitor when the element enters the viewport
const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries, observer) => {
  // Check if the observed element is visible in the viewport
  if (entries[0].isIntersecting) {
    // Call the function to load the widget or heavy content
    loadWidget();
    // Stop observing after the content has loaded
    observer.unobserve(entries[0].target);
  }
});

// Start observing the target element
observer.observe(widget);

// Function to load widget content
function loadWidget() {
  // Example: dynamically import a module or create elements
  import('./widget.js').then(module => {
    module.initWidget(widget);
  });
}</code></pre>

  <h3>Use Resource Hints</h3>

  <p>Browsers can establish early connections to external servers.</p>

  <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
  <pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>&lt;link rel="preconnect" href="https://analytics.example.com"&gt;</code></pre>

  <p>This reduces DNS and connection setup time.</p>

  <h3>Self-Host Critical Libraries</h3>

  <p>If licensing permits, hosting libraries locally can reduce external network overhead.</p>

  <p><strong>Benefits:</strong></p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Better caching control</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Fewer DNS lookups</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Improved reliability</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Split Large Bundles</h3>

  <p>Large third-party libraries can often be partially loaded using code splitting or tree shaking.</p>

  <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
  <pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>import("chart-library")</code></pre>

  <p>This ensures that code loads only when needed.</p>

  <h3>Lazy Loading Patterns</h3>

  <p>Lazy loading should follow predictable patterns.</p>

  <h4>Scroll-based Lazy Loading</h4>

  <p>Load scripts when a component enters the viewport. Use the IntersectionObserver API.</p>

  <h4>Interaction-based Lazy Loading</h4>

  <p>Load functionality after user interaction.</p>

  <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
  <ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
    <li class="vf-list__item">Open modal</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Click button</li>
    <li class="vf-list__item">Expand widget</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>Post-load Lazy Loading</h4>

  <p>Load scripts after the page becomes interactive.</p>

  <pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>&lt;script&gt;
  // Wait until the entire page has finished loading
  window.addEventListener("load", () => {
    // Initialize non-critical functionality, e.g., analytics
    loadAnalytics();
  });

  // Example function to initialize analytics
  function loadAnalytics() {
    // Load external analytics script or initialize tracking logic
    const script = document.createElement('script');
    script.src = 'analytics.js';
    script.async = true; // Load asynchronously to avoid blocking
    document.body.appendChild(script);
  }
&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>

